body:
It is currently possible to use `class-string` as a type, and the assertion with the function call `class_exists` works like a charm.

Using it with interfaces is not so straightforward though. The `ReflectionClass` constructor accepts a `class-string`, but it is also possible to pass an interface name to it.

Consider the following code:
```
<?php

/**
 * @psalm-param class-string $className
 */
function funA(string $className): ReflectionClass
{
    return new ReflectionClass($className);
}

function funB(string $className)
{
    if (class_exists($className)) {
        return funA($className);
    }

    if (interface_exists($className)) {
        return funA($className);
    }
}
```

In this case, psalm will raise an error saying that I'm passing a `string` where a `class-string` was expected, after the `interface_exists` check.

If I add the `class-string` type to `$className` of `funB` psalm will say `class_exists($className)` is a redundant condition.

I believe that making all interfaces to be considered valid `class-string` values would end up being too generic, but it would be nice to have a sort of hierarchy then, like `type-string`, `interface-string` and `class-string`, where both `interface-string` and `class-string` values could be assigned to a `type-string` variable/parameter/return.
